AGI - Imbarazzo e indignazione in Palermo> after the news that last April 15 the Mafia boss of Palermo Tommaso Lo Presti>, celebrated the silver wedding in the Pantheon of illustrious Sicilians, > the Church of San Domenico>, which welcomes the remains of Giovanni Falcone. The boss had been discarded shortly after a dozen years in prison, and with his wife, she also convicted of mafia. He had decided to party for the twenty-fifth, first with a Mass in this suggestive and symbolic place, place of state funerals like that for the prefect Carlo Alberto Dalla Chiesa, and then with some neo-melodics in a private villa. On the daily newspaper "La Repubblica" Maria Falcone is said "indignated, cherished for the silver wedding of the boss celebrated in the church of San Domenico, it is as if that mafia had made a bully against John, but John from above does not care for them".
&nbsp;
The rector of San Domenico assures to have known only after the couple and that the offer received from the boss will not be returned, but used to "do good to those who need it">. But this does not seem to be enough for those who felt injured and there are those who speak of "grave rubbish to memory and to the city" and point their finger even against certain sectors of the Church not yet clear in their behaviors.&nbsp;The Church of San Domenico built since 1640, with the largest cult building in Sicily, is of the Order of Dominicans and not under the canonical jurisdiction of the archdiocese of Palermo. Since the mid-19th century the Pantheon of the Illustri of Sicily, men and women who have distinguished themselves, and among them, since 2015, Giovanni Falcone.
&nbsp;
On 23 April, at the funeral of Vincenzo Augustine, in the cathedral, the archbishop of Palermo, Corrado Lorefice, had spoken net words, inviting an "active and fruitful resistance to the mafia and the many forms of structured evil that bloodslides the streets of the city, spreads affliction in the houses and in the families, plans depistaggi, buys silences and connivenze also among representatives of the political state". In a city that "has witnessed the sacrifice of so many men and women of the institutions, civil society and the Church of Palermo", it is necessary to renew the commitment, incalzava Don Corrado, for the "construction of a city of just and solidarity, free from the 'structures of sin' mafiose and from corruption and imperant falsehood".
&nbsp;
In this same Pantheon rest, > from 23 March last, the remains of another illustrious Sicilian, Giuseppe Tomasi of Lampedusa, with the intention declared to deliver and exalt the topicality of the message of the writer who stands in his ability to analyze the period of transformations and crisis in which his most famous novel, "Il Gattopardo", is set, and to tell about the Sicily by delineating human types. But, among the more or less noble fauna cited in the book, hyenas, jackals, sheep, catwomen and lions, the message that is an act of accusation against an inability and an inadequacy, almost structural, to the true change: "If we want everything to remain as it is, we have to change everything."

